@Linda Jo 

The first thing I think of when ALLO comes up is allophones. That’s a linguistics term for two manifestations of the same phoneme (basically, the same sound) which don’t make for changes in meaning. For example, the /p/ in “pot” and the /p/ in “spot”.  The former is said with an aspiration of air which is not produced in the latter. Native speakers don’t even realize they pronounce the two differently, and dictionaries usually don’t make note of it. 

